article.description: Lauren Jackson had 20 points, eight rebounds and four steals to lead the Storm to a 78-70 victory over the Sparks.
article.headline: Pulled left hamstring sidelines 'Mique
article.linkText: Jackson nears double-double as streaking Storm stop Sparks
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As the WNBA's leading scorer watched from the
bench, the Seattle's Lauren Jackson took command against the Los
Angeles Sparks.

Jackson had 20 points, eight rebounds and four steals to lead
the Storm to a 78-70 victory over the Sparks on Saturday night.

"We've been working on our offense all season," said Jackson,
who made three of five 3-point shots. "The last couple of games,
things have just started to flow a lot better. Hopefully, we can
finish the season strong."

The Sparks' Chamique Holdsclaw, the league's top leading scorer,
missed the game with a pulled left hamstring.

"I hurt it the last game and it was just really tight,"
Holdsclaw said. "I got treatment and Marco [Nunez], the trainer,
says I can't go. I'll be ready next game."

Betty Lennox added 16 points and Sue Bird had 14 points and tied
a career high with eight assists for the Storm (10-10), who have
won three of five after losing four in a row.

Lisa Leslie scored 19 points and Mwadi Mabika added 14 points
for the Sparks (10-8), who fell three games behind first-place
Sacramento in the Western Conference.

Raffaella Masciadri replaced Holdsclaw and made the first start
of her two-year WNBA career.

The Storm used an 10-1 surge to take a 36-28 lead with 28.5
seconds left in the first half. Jackson and Lennox each made a
3-point shot during the run.

Los Angeles narrowed its deficit to 47-43 but Seattle used a
13-2 spree to build a 60-45 lead with 11:23 to play. Jackson made a
pair of 3-point baskets.

"The 3-pointers by Lauren Jackson were huge," Storm coach Anne
Donovan said. "We just haven't shot well from the 3-point line.
But the last three games, we're starting to click again."

The Sparks drew to within 75-70 on Nikki Teasley's 3-pointer
with 30.7 seconds remaining. But Francesca Zara made two free
throws with 28.6 seconds left to give the Storm a 77-70 lead.

Seattle scored 19 points off 13 Los Angeles turnovers and
outrebounded the Sparks 31-24.
